ce:section.ce:para:
The selectivity of the organic probe is the most important factor relative to other probes, because the molecules can be designed according to the radius and electrical properties of the targeted ions (Table 2
                     ). In this work, the coumarin parent ring is modified with a polyhydroxy structure and can achieve the specific capture of iron ions. Through this combination, the optical properties of the coumarin parent ring can be affected due to the characteristics of the attracting electrons of the iron ions, and iron ion sensing can be achieved by analyzing the optical signal. The chemical sensing behavior of TPC molecules were screened with various metal ions, including transition metal ions (Mn2+, Ni2+, Cu2+, Zn2+, Ni2+, Fe3+, and Co2+), alkali metal ions (Na+ and K+), and alkaline earth metal ions (Ca2+ and Ba2+). Among these metal ions, Fe3+ exhibits a strong quenching effect, as shown in Fig. 3
                     . In addition, the tendency of some transition metals and heavy metals, such as Fe3+, Cu2+, Cd2+, Hg2+ and Pb2+, to quench luminescence by electron and/or energy transfer processes is well known. Herein, the recognition unit of our probe can be selectively combined with iron ions. The effect of photoelectron transfer (PET) on N atoms happens upon combination of the probe with Fe3+, causing the fluorescence quenching of coumarin units. However, the TPC sensors cannot be combined with other ions, and without the PET effect, the probe cannot be quenched by other ions.
